I would be happy to send a S.A.S.E. if you send me your address.  Thank you!<br />\nI think the book was The Shy Stegosaurus of Cricket Creek - I never read it, but I have a book called The Shy Stegosaurus of Indian Creek, which I think is the sequel - you can see it here in my dinosaur books collection.<br />\nThere have been a lot of dinosaur finds lately - did you see the dinosaur mummy special on the National Geographic channel the other day?  I missed it :( Hopefully they will replay it.<br />\nThanks again!<br />\n-Brian',0,1,1,0,0,0,'2007-12-14 10:15:48'),(461,'922a4a6183b0c82601c18756f4349a03',1,214,'Welcome to Collectors\' Quest','Welcome to Collectors\' Quest - the destination place for all collectors.\nGet started by <a href=\"http://www.collectorsquest.com/collection/create.html\">adding your own collection</a> or just click around to find some great <a href=\"http://www.collectorsquest.com/collection.html\">collections</a> and <a href=\"http://www.collectorsquest.com/community/collectors.html\">collectors</a>.\nWhat\'s in your collection?',1,0,0,0,0,0,'2007-12-16 10:56:42'),(462,'9d55b2238d9b7771ebf80e4edf878481',200,52,'RE: RE: RE: RE: Your Dino Collection','Hi Brian,<br />\nThanks for the reply. After I sent the last email, I looked at some of your collections and I saw Egg Stealers and Earth Shakers from Dinosaurs A Celebration and the The Shy Stegosaurus of Indian Creek. I remember that book from elementary school.<br />\nI am not sure how many of the Dinosaurs Attack comics were published. The cover of the first issue is #35 Lady in Distress from the card series.<br />\nHere is a link to the whole card series. The fronts and backs of cards and stickers and wrappers. http://www.bobheffner.com/dinosaursattack/<br />\nHere are a couple links about Dinosaurs Attack -  http://members.tripod.com/TheWrapper/dinotax.html<br />\nhttp://members.tripod.com/TheWrapper/gerani.html  (I highlight to be able to read these two pages.)<br />\nHere is a link inside MileHigh to the comic book, Dinosaurs Attack #1. http://www.milehighcomics.com/cgi-bin/backissue.cgi?action=fullsize&amp;issue=25267019588%201<br />\nMileHigh is a good reference to check for comics. http://www.milehighcomics.com/<br />\nI know what you mean about buying a comic book because of the cover. I have quite a lot because of the cover. What good is a comic book without art or story. The art catches the eye and the story keeps you coming back for more.<br />\nI like the Classic Illustrated comic book series. It features famous old classic stories.In the Classics family there is a comic in the World Around Us series published by Gilberton called \"The Illustrated Story of Prehistoric Animals\". This book has a square or perfect bound like the Dino - Celebration book. It has a $.25 cover when other comics of the time had a $.10 or $.12 cover price and approx. 64+ pages.<br />\nThis link takes you to the series World Around Us. http://www.classicscentral.com/world.htm<br />\nThis link takes you to the  \"The Illustrated Story of Prehistoric Animals\". http://www.classicscentral.com/wau/wau15b.jpg<br />\nAbout the Wackosaurs stickers is that the same dino character has another name in the series. Series1a is Frizzy Liz and 2b is Wailin\' Wally and so on. The checklists have even more variations.<br />\nIf you are trying to finish the Dinosaurs Attack card set and you need some cards, let me know, I have some duplicates. Send wantlist with the S.A.S.E. for the missing wrapper/pack to:<br />\nJohn Amble<br />\n335D W. Cedar St.<br />\nSequim, WA  98382<br />\nGoodbye and Thanks Again,<br />\nJohn(jac)<br />\nI leave you with ............<br />\nI missed the dinosaur mummy special on the National Geographic channel, but It would be something I would look at.<br />\nHere is an article<br />\nOSLO, Norway - Remains of a bus-sized prehistoric \"monster\" reptile found on a remote Arctic island may be a new species never before recorded by science, researchers said Tuesday.<br />\nInitial excavation of a site on the Svalbard islands in August yielded the remains, teeth, skull fragments and vertebrae of a reptile estimated to measure nearly 40 feet long, said Joern Harald Hurum of the University of Oslo.<br />\n\"It seems the monster is a new species,\" he told The Associated Press.<br />\nThe reptile appears be the same species as another sea predator whose remains were found nearby on Svalbard last year. His team described those 150-million-year-old remains as belonging to a short-necked plesiosaur measuring more than 30 feet â€” \"as long as a bus ... with teeth larger than cucumbers.\"<br />\nThe short-necked plesiosaur was a voracious reptile often compared to the Tyrannosaurus rex of the oceans.<br />\nMark Evans, a plesiosaur expert at the Leicester City Museums in Britain, said he not know enough about the Norwegian find to comment on it specifically. But he said new types of the sea reptiles are being found regularly.<br />\n\"We are regularly seeing new species of plesiosaurs popping up â€” in a way because, in the past 10 or 15 years, there has been what we call a renaissance in plesiosaur research,\" Evans said by telephone.<br />\nHurum said the team had only managed to excavate a 3-meter (yard) area of the find. The Norwegian-led team plans to present more detailed findings early next year, and return to Svalbard, 300 miles north of Norway\'s mainland, to excavate further next year.<br />\n___<br />\nOn the Net:<br />\nhttp://www.nhm.uio.no/pliosaurus/index.html',0,1,0,0,0,0,'2007-12-17 02:15:39'),(463,'5f8ac725cf4a1fb2043f9af51fac80b2',59,5,'RE: RE: can\'t login to get mail!','I don\'t have/didn\'t login into 2 accounts.<br />\nAnd while it is working now, I didn\'t get mail sent to me on the 14th until later.  There must have been some sort of mail server hiccup...<br />\nAgain, it\'s all working now.  (Just makes me really nervous when I\'ve got interviews going etc. because I\'d have to start them all over again 